    <center><h1 style="color: orangered;"; ><p style="font-size: larger;"> <u>COVID19</u> </p></h1></center>

        <ol type="I">
            <h3 style="color: rgb(167, 15, 159);"><li>Covid19 définition :</li></h3>
            <b>
            <p >COVID-19 (short for "coronavirus disease 2019") is an infectious respiratory illness caused by the SARS-CoV-2 virus, which was first identified in Wuhan, China in December 2019. The disease quickly spread and was declared a global pandemic by the World Health Organization (WHO) in March 2020.</p>

            <p>COVID-19 primarily spreads through respiratory droplets when an infected person talks, coughs, or sneezes, and can also spread by touching a surface contaminated with the virus and then touching one's face. The symptoms of COVID-19 can range from mild to severe, and can include fever, cough, shortness of breath, fatigue, muscle or body aches, headache, new loss of taste or smell, sore throat, congestion or runny nose, nausea or vomiting, and diarrhea. Some people with COVID-19 may have no symptoms at all.</p>
                
            <p>COVID-19 has had a significant impact on the world, causing illness and death, disrupting daily life, and creating economic and social challenges. Prevention measures, such as wearing masks, social distancing, and vaccination, have been effective in reducing the spread of the virus.</p>
            </b>

            
            <h3 style="color: rgb(167, 15, 159);"><li>Prevention rules and precautions against covid 19:</li></h3>
            <p><b>To prevent the spread of COVID-19, it is important to follow a set of prevention measures and precautions. These measures include:</b></p>
            <ol type="1">
                <div>
                <li>Getting vaccinated is one of the most effective ways to protect yourself and others from COVID-19. Vaccines are safe and effective at preventing serious illness, hospitalization, and death.</li>
                <li>Mask-wearing: Wearing a mask can help prevent the spread of COVID-19, particularly in crowded settings or indoors with poor ventilation. Masks should cover the nose and mouth and fit snugly around the face.</li>
                <li>Social distancing: Maintaining at least 6 feet of distance between yourself and others can help reduce the spread of COVID-19, particularly in public spaces or large gatherings.</li>
                <li>Hand hygiene: Regularly washing your hands with soap and water for at least 20 seconds or using hand sanitizer can help kill germs and reduce the spread of COVID-19.</li>
                <li>Avoiding crowds: Large gatherings or crowded spaces can increase the risk of spreading COVID-19. It is important to avoid such situations whenever possible.</li>
                <li>Quarantine and isolation: If you have been exposed to someone with COVID-19 or are experiencing symptoms, it is important to stay home and avoid contact with others to prevent the spread of the virus.</li>
                <li>Cleaning and disinfecting: Regularly cleaning and disinfecting frequently touched surfaces, such as doorknobs, light switches, and countertops, can help reduce the spread of COVID-19.</li>
                </div>
            
            <p><b>It is important to follow these measures consistently and to stay informed about any changes in guidance or recommendations from public health authorities.</b></p>
            </ol>

            <h3 style="color: rgb(167, 15, 159);"><li>vaccines with the different vaccines that can be used today :</li></h3>
            <ol type="1">
                <li>Pfizer-BioNTech : Ce vaccin utilise la technologie de l'ARN messager pour stimuler la production de protéines virales, ce qui déclenche une réponse immunitaire. Il nécessite deux doses administrées à trois semaines d'intervalle et est approuvé pour une utilisation chez les personnes âgées de 16 ans et plus.</li>
                <li>Moderna : Ce vaccin utilise également la technologie de l'ARN messager pour stimuler la production de protéines virales. Il nécessite deux doses administrées à quatre semaines d'intervalle et est approuvé pour une utilisation chez les personnes âgées de 18 ans et plus.</li>
                <li>Johnson & Johnson (Janssen) : Ce vaccin utilise un vecteur viral inactivé pour stimuler une réponse immunitaire. Il ne nécessite qu'une seule dose et est approuvé pour une utilisation chez les personnes âgées de 18 ans et plus.</li>
                <li>AstraZeneca : Ce vaccin utilise également un vecteur viral inactivé pour stimuler une réponse immunitaire. Il nécessite deux doses administrées à quatre semaines d'intervalle et est approuvé pour une utilisation chez les personnes âgées de 18 ans et plus, sauf dans certains pays où l'âge minimum peut varier.</li>
            </ol>
            
        </ol>

